Chi's Second Prototyping Rule, also known as the "20% solution," is a design thinking principle coined by Donald A. Norman, a cognitive scientist and design theorist. It suggests that when designing a product or service, it's essential to focus on delivering a minimum viable product (MVP) that meets 20% of the users' needs, rather than trying to create a perfect solution that meets all of their needs from the start.
The idea behind this rule is that by delivering a minimalist solution early on, you can quickly gather feedback from users and iterate on the design to meet their full needs. This approach allows for a more efficient and effective design process, as it focuses on delivering a working product that can be improved upon rather than trying to create a perfect product from the start.
In other words, Chi's Second Prototyping Rule encourages designers to start with a simple, basic version of their product and then build upon it based on user feedback, rather than trying to create a complex and perfect solution all at once. This approach can help designers avoid the common trap of over-designing and over-engineering their products, which can lead to confusion and frustration among users.
For example, let's say you're designing a new mobile app for tracking personal expenses. Rather than trying to create a fully-featured app with every possible function from the start, you might start with a simple MVP that allows users to easily track their income and expenses. Once the MVP is launched, you can gather feedback from users and iterate on the design to add additional features and improve the user experience.
Overall, Chi's Second Prototyping Rule is a valuable tool for designers looking to create user-centered products that meet the needs of their target audience.
